==English==

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|fr|meringue|notext=1}}. Historically, it was believed that meringue was invented in and named for the Swiss village of {{w|Meiringen}},<ref name="McGee">Harold McGee, ''On Food and Cooking: The Science and Lore of the Kitchen''</ref> but the term is now thought to derive instead from {{etyl|dum|en}} {{m|dum|meringue||light evening meal}}, of unclear origin:<ref name="McGee"/>
* perhaps from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|merenda||light evening meal}},<ref name="McGee"/> or
* perhaps from {{etyl|dum|-}} *{{m|dum||meren|to dip or soak bread}}, from {{etyl|odt|-}} *{{m|odt||meren}}, ''itself'' of unclear origin:
** perhaps from {{cog|gem-pro|*marjaną||to grind, pound}}, from {{cog|ine-pro|*mer-||to rub, pack}}.
** perhaps from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*marhin||soup of bread and wine or water}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*mark-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*merk-||wet}}.

Compare {{cog|gml|meringe}} (from {{m|gml|mern||to dip bread in wine}}), {{cog|gmh|merunge}} (from {{m|gmh|mëren||to soak bread in wine or water for dinner}}), {{cog|ang|merian||to purify, cleanse, test}}.

